        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       Purdue and opioid misuse 
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      Purdue Pharma, owned by the Sackler family, became the face of the US opioid epidemic following the release of OxyContin in 1996. Marketed as a low-risk painkiller, OxyContin contributed to many <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-28-06-2025-overdose-related-deaths" target="_blank">overdose-related deaths</a>. As addictions soared and scrutiny intensified, Purdue faced lawsuits accusing it of fueling the crisis by downplaying addiction risks and aggressively promoting trade. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/prescription-opioid-deaths-oxycontin-high-dosage-2011-rise.jpg" alt="Deaths linked to prescription opioids, including OxyContin, which came in high dosages rose rapidly until 201" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
           Deaths linked to prescription opioids, including OxyContin, which came in high dosages rose rapidly until 2011. Credits: AP Photo</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           The company filed for bankruptcy in 2019 and proposed a settlement that would restructure Purdue into a public benefit corporation. In 2020, they pleaded guilty to failing to maintain an effective program to prevent drugs from being diverted to the black market, providing misleading information to the DEA, and paying doctors in a speakers program to encourage them to write more prescriptions.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         The US Supreme Court rejected the settlement proposal in 2024, ruling that the Sacklers couldn’t be shielded from future civil lawsuits without agreeing to bankruptcy themselves. Though the company’s proposed settlement was part of over $50B in total opioid-related settlements, its legacy remains tarnished, symbolizing the consequences of corporate negligence and revenue-driven public health decisions. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="4px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Cipla’s patent turnover
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      In 1972, Yusuf Khwaja Hamied, visionary leader of Cipla, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-28-06-2025-proposed-a-project" target="_blank">proposed a project</a> to make India self-reliant in pharmaceuticals to then PM Indira Gandhi. Propranolol invented by Imperial Chemical Industries in England, in 1963, was a drug against heart disease. Hamied questioned if Indians should be deprived of essential drugs because of the inventor’s racial discrimination. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/cipla-tamiflu-copy-avian-flu-2006-roche.jpg" alt="In 2006, during the avian flu epidemic, Cipla defied multinational company Roche by copying Tamiflu" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            In 2006, during the avian flu epidemic, Cipla defied multinational company Roche by copying Tamiflu. Credits: News Bytes</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           This resonated with Gandhi and prompted India to change its patent laws. The updated law said a company could not patent any end product or compound, but the process to make that product and that too for a period of seven years. This allowed Hamied to produce his copycat versions, called generics, by slightly changing the manufacturing process. 
            </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       Hamied furthered his mission by reverse-engineering drugs for AIDS and avian flu. Critics argued that bypassing the traditional intellectual property rights protection undermined the incentive for drug innovation. However, Cipla argues that it was a necessary step to ensure medicines reached those who needed them the most. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      With Blackstone eyeing the entire 33.47% promoter stake in Cipla, an 88-year-old slice of India's history is about to enter the museums. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>

